{
  "style": "IEEE",
  "texts": [
    "Additionally, aligning to one course using fine-tuning may not align the LLM with other courses, especially if those courses have differing or even contradictory requirements.",
    "As an example, our introductory programming courses are usually very restrictive on the libraries that students may use, while upper-year courses relax these restrictions.",
    "Finetuning an LLM to simultaneously be restrictive and relaxed is difficult.",
    "Furthermore, nonexpert users who wish to course-align in this way may not have the skills required to do so.Second, fine-tuning is commonly used for adding downstream skills to a pre-trained LLM, but not necessarily for increasing an LLM's knowledge [6].",
    "That is, it is possible to provide the LLM with a set of input/output pairs that teaches it how to respond to a given query, but not necessarily what to say."
  ],
